{
  "id": "019ce63c-2716-71d2-b76a-75a1a2fdb6ae",
  "content": "## Decision: Shared Playwright MCP server via corvia-dev\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-13\n\n**Problem:** Each Claude Code session spawned its own Playwright MCP process via stdio `command` transport in `.mcp.json`. With 4 concurrent sessions, this meant 9 extra processes (npm + sh + node per session) consuming 573MB RAM total — 11.7x more than the single shared corvia MCP server (49MB).\n\n**Decision:** Run Playwright MCP as a single shared HTTP server on port 8050, managed by corvia-dev alongside corvia-server and corvia-dashboard.\n\n**Changes:**\n- `.mcp.json`: Playwright transport changed from `command` (npx spawn) to `type: http` pointing at `http://127.0.0.1:8050/mcp`\n- `tools/corvia-dev/corvia_dev/services.py`: Added `playwright-mcp` as a tier-0 managed service with TCP health checks, auto-restart with backoff\n- `.devcontainer/scripts/post-start.sh`: Removed manual Playwright startup (corvia-dev handles lifecycle)\n\n**Port choice:** 8050 instead of 8022 to avoid collision with Vite's auto-increment range (8021 → 8022, 8023... when ports conflict during restarts).\n\n**Health check:** Uses `tcp` protocol because Playwright MCP returns 400 on GET `/` and `/mcp` (expects MCP protocol headers), and `/sse` is a streaming endpoint that would hang HTTP health checks.\n\n**Impact:** Saves ~380MB RAM and 6 processes per workspace. All Claude sessions share one Playwright instance with supervised restarts.",
  "source_version": "mcp",
  "scope_id": "corvia",
  "workstream": "main",
